taxonRemarks: Shumard's Oak
habitat: Mixed pine-oak upland forest along a large reservoir
verbatimAttributes: Large oak loaded with acorns. Leaves deeply lobed and bristle-tipped, margins sharply acute. Lower surface of leaves glabrous. Lower branches of tree spreading, not drooping as in Q. Palustris. Mature leaf blades greater than 12 cm long, terminal buds glabrous.
associatedTaxa: Quercus alba, Pinus echinata, Ostrya virginiana
locality: Garland County, Arkansas. Lake Ouachita, Lena Landing Recreation Area, tent campground by marina

taxonRemarks: Shumard's Oak
habitat: Central Basin area. A small group of trees 10 feet from a paved road leading into the park.
verbatimAttributes: Family: Fagaceae Common name: Shumard Oak large tree with thick, gray/brown bark with shallow dark furrows and scaly ridges that are rather thick. The leaves are simple, alternating with 7-8 deepish lobes that are bristle tipped signifying that it is a red oak type. On the back of the leaves are tufts of hair in the axils. The acorns of this species are shallow cupped that enclose less than a third of the nut.Species similar to this are Q. rubra, Q. velutina, Q. texana, and Q. palustris.
associatedTaxa: Cercis canadensis, Rhamnus caroliniana, Quercus species
locality: Barfield Crescent Park, 697 Veteran Pkwy, Murfreesboro, TN 37127

taxonRemarks: Shumard's Oak
verbatimAttributes: This specimen is very large (DBH several feet wide), and is the largest tree in the back yard of this old home site. Leaves with bristle tips (red oak-type) and hairs in the leaf vein axils. Leaf bases various (tapered, abruptly-tapered, and slightly oblique). Acorn cup only enclosing the base of the nut. Acorn approx. 1" long
